  <h2>Key Findings</h2>
  <ul class="findings fade-up">
    <li>RADV dominates prompt processing across Qwen3.5 models (50-280% faster than AMDVLK). Token generation is typically tied between drivers since it's bandwidth-bound.</li>
    <li>AMDVLK only wins on GPT-OSS-120B pp (661 vs 596 RADV). It no longer leads tg on MoE models.</li>
    <li>ROCm requires <code>-mmp 0</code> or models hang during load. Best for some dense models like GLM-4.7 and Qwen3.5-27B. Crashes with FA enabled on GPT-OSS-120B.</li>
    <li>MXFP4 outperforms Q4_K_M for QAT-trained MoE models. Post-hoc MXFP4 on BF16 underperforms standard quants.</li>
    <li>Qwen3.5 dense models hit an architecture-level tg bottleneck. The 27B tops out at ~12 t/s and the 9B at ~22 t/s regardless of backend.</li>
    <li>Sampling params transform quality results. Unsloth-recommended params (presence_penalty 1.5, top_k 20, thinking mode via chat-template-kwargs) made the difference between 0/10 and 10/10 on several models.</li>
    <li>LeetCode is the new LRU cache. 10 of 12 models score a perfect 59/59 on classic algorithmic problems from Two Sum through Min Window Substring. Only Qwen3.5-4B (54) and 9B (51) miss any. Training data saturation makes traditional coding benchmarks useless for differentiation.</li>
    <li>The polyglot benchmark reveals what LRU cache and LeetCode hide. 15 models score 10/10 on LRU cache and 10 score 59/59 on LeetCode, but the polyglot gauntlet tops out at 14/65. Three-way tie between GPT-OSS-120B, GPT-OSS-20B, and Gemma-4-31B. The 20B matches its 120B sibling identically in 3 minutes vs 8.</li>
    <li>Dense beats MoE on structured output. Gemma-4-31B (dense, 14/65) outperforms its MoE sibling 26B-A4B (10/65) on bash despite being 5x slower. Qwen3-30B is the only model to score on Go (3/10).</li>
    <li>T2 (cron), T5 (FastAPI), and T6 (Sinatra) remain unsolved at 0/10 across all 14 model runs. These single-shot challenges exceed current local model capabilities.</li>
  </ul>

